patches are organised aggregates of lymphoid tissue found in the \u003Cstrong\u003Esmall intestine\u003C/strong\u003E, specifically in the ileum. They are located in the lamina propria and submucosa. They are visible to the naked eye as slightly raised areas on the anti-mesenteric border of the intestine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epancreas\u003C/strong\u003E contains scattered lymphoid tissue but not organised Peyer\u0027s patches. The \u003Cstrong\u003Espleen\u003C/strong\u003E is a secondary lymphoid organ but does not contain Peyer\u0027s patches. The \u003Cstrong\u003Elarge intestine\u003C/strong\u003E contains lymphoid follicles but not Peyer\u0027s patches. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eliver\u003C/strong\u003E contains immune cells but not organised lymphoid tissue like Peyer\u0027s patches.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPeyer\u0027s patches are part of the gut-associated lymphoid tissue (GALT) and play an important role in immune surveillance and the generation of immune responses to antigens in the intestinal lumen. They are covered by specialised epithelium containing M cells that sample and transport antigens from the lumen to underlying immune cells.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Peyer\u0027s patches are aggregated lymphoid follicles found in the ileum of the small intestine that form part of the gut-associated lymphoid tissue.","Peyer\u0027s patches play a crucial role in immune surveillance of the intestinal lumen and mucosal immunity."],"references":["Nightingale, J. M. (2012). Applied anatomy and physiology of the gastrointestinal tract (GIT). Gastrointestinal Tract Imaging E-Book: Gastrointestinal Tract Imaging E-Book, 45.","Podolsky, D. K., Camilleri, M., Fitz, J. G., Kalloo, A. N., Shanahan, F., \u0026 Wang, T. C. (Eds.). (2015). Yamada\u0027s textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons.","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (